sols:
Our first step will be to extend the cup to look like a cone and label
everything as shown in the diagram.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{ConaCola.jpg}
\caption{ConaCola.jpg}
\end{figure}

Now, we can compute the value of \emph{y} quickly via similar triangles
(the big triangle and the one with side length 3),

\begin{align*}\frac{20+y}{6} = \frac{y}{3}\end{align*}

and this gives \emph{y} = 20cm. However, notice in the question that
there are several different units everywhere and so for consistency we
should use a single unit (metres). As shown, let $x_{i}^{*}$ be a sample
point between 0 and 0.2 (0 to 20cm), measured from the top of the cup.
Then, at this point, the radius, labeled as $r_{i}$ is

\begin{align*}\frac{r_{i}}{0.4-x_{i}^{*}} = \frac{0.06}{0.4} = \frac{3}{20}\end{align*}

and isolating gives

\begin{align*}r_{i} = \frac{3(0.4-x_{i}^{*})}{20} = \frac{1.2-3x_{i}^{*}}{20}\end{align*}

Now, using the volume of a cylinder formula, we have

\begin{align*}V_{i} = \pi r_{i}^{2} \Delta x = \pi \bigg( \frac{1.2-3x_{i}^{*}}{20}\bigg)^2 \Delta x\end{align*}

Using the mass formula with $\delta$ as density, we have

\begin{align*}m_{i} = \delta V_{i} = 1000\pi \bigg( \frac{1.2-3x_{i}^{*}}{20}\bigg)^2 \Delta x\end{align*}

Using the force formula, we have

\begin{align*}F_{i} = m_{i} g = (9.8)1000\pi \bigg( \frac{1.2-3x_{i}^{*}}{20}\bigg)^2 \Delta x\end{align*}

and finally, using the work formula, we can compute that the work done
at the sample point is

\begin{align*}W_{i} = F_{i} d = (9.8)1000\pi \bigg( \frac{1.2-3x_{i}^{*}}{20}\bigg)^2 \Delta x (0.1 + x_{i}^{*})\end{align*}

where we added 0.1m (10cm) to the distance \emph{d} above since we are
using a straw that is 10 cm above the cup. Hence, summing all these
pieces gives

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n \to \infty}\sum_{i=1}^{n} W_{i} &= \lim_{n \to \infty}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(9.8)1000\pi \bigg( \frac{1.2-3x_{i}^{*}}{20}\bigg)^2 \Delta x (0.1 + x_{i}^{*}) \\
&= \int_{0}^{20} (9.8)1000\pi \bigg( \frac{1.2-3x}{20}\bigg)^2(0.1 + x)  \, dx \end{align*}

completing the question (we do not need to evaluate this integral).

hints:
The following formulas will probably be useful

\texttt{Volume~of~a~cylinder~=~pi~x~radius}\textsuperscript{\texttt{2}}\texttt{~x~height}

\texttt{Mass~=~volume~x~density}

\texttt{Force~=~acceleration~x~mass~=~gravity~x~mass~=~9.8~x~mass}

\texttt{Work~=~force~x~displacement}
